&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Alison Wong of New York City says going into the new year with a clean slate makes her feel like she can get a fresh start. "I feel like having everything cleaned allows me to enjoy the New Year celebrations."&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Setting yourself up for success&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Wong adds that many Chinese traditions around the new year, like cleaning or eating sweets, are all about setting the mood for the year ahead. "A lot of it feels about intent. [Eating] sweet treats in the morning not only signals a new change for the new year, but it's about bringing in only sweet moments in life.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-44562" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4608;         --source-height: 3456;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20